    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Nader the Green: Is He a Spoiler?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Andy Humm letter deplores presidential candidacy of Ralph Nader</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Ralph Nader's campaign as the Green Party candidate for president (news article, June 26) may deliver the election to a right-wing Republican, George W. Bush, damaging progressive interests for a generation.</p>
        <p>Mr. Nader is not a member of any political party, not even the Greens. If he had really wanted to generate progress on vital issues like the corporate domination of our political system, he should have challenged Al Gore in the primaries and moved the Democratic Party to the left.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Ralph Nader's campaign as the Green Party candidate for president (news article, June 26) may deliver the election to a right-wing Republican, George W. Bush, damaging progressive interests for a generation.</p>
        <p>Mr. Nader is not a member of any political party, not even the Greens. If he had really wanted to generate progress on vital issues like the corporate domination of our political system, he should have challenged Al Gore in the primaries and moved the Democratic Party to the left.</p>
        <p>Until we reform winner-take-all elections in this country, minor parties will be spoilers, making their point to the opposite effect of their stated purposes.</p>
        <p>ANDY HUMM  New York, June 26, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is the editor of Social Policy magazine.</p>
      </block>
